# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aldolase-b
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] 1,3-Bisphosphoglycerate is the conjugate base of 1,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] It is phosphorylated at the number 1 and 3 carbons.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The result of this phosphorylation gives 1,3BPG important biological properties such as the ability to donate a phosphate group to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) in order to form the energy storage molecule adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00118 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 1.2.1.12 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] 1,3BPG is a macroergic metabolic intermediate in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] It is created by the exergonic oxidation of the aldehyde in glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The result of this oxidation is the conversion of the aldehyde group into a carboxylic acid group which drives the formation of an acyl phosphate bond.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The latter reaction is the only step in the glycolytic pathway in which NAD+ is converted into NADH.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The formation reaction of 1,3BPG requires the presence of an enzyme called glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The high-energy acyl phosphate bond of 1,3BPG is important in respiration as it assists in the formation of ATP.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The molecule of ATP created during the following reaction is the first molecule produced during respiration.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The transfer of an inorganic phosphate from the carboxyl group on 1,3BPG to ADP to form ATP is reversible due to a low ΔG.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] This is as a result of one acyl phosphate bond being cleaved whilst another is created.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] This reaction is not naturally spontaneous and requires the presence of a catalyst.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] This role is performed by the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] During the reaction phosphoglycerate kinase undergoes a substrate induced conformational change similar to another metabolic enzyme called hexokinase.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Because two molecules of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate are formed during glycolysis from one molecule of glucose, 1,3BPG can be said to be responsible for two of the ten molecules of ATP produced during the entire process.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Glycolysis also uses two molecules of ATP in its initial stages as a committed and irreversible step.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] For this reason glycolysis is not reversible and has a net produce of 2 molecules of ATP and two of NADH.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The two molecules of NADH themselves go on to produce approximately 3 molecules of ATP each.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] 1,3-BPG has a very similar role in the Calvin cycle to its role in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] For this reason both reactions are said to be analogous.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] However the reaction pathway is effectively reversed.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The only other major difference between the two reactions is that NADPH is used as an electron donor in the calvin cycle whilst NAD+ is used as an electron acceptor in glycolysis.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] In this reaction cycle 1,3BPG originates from 3-phosphoglycerate and is made into glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate by the action of specific enzymes.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Contrary to the similar reactions of the glycolytic pathway, 1,3BPG in the Calvin cycle does not produce ATP but instead uses it.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] For this reason it can be considered to be an irreversible and committed step in the cycle.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The outcome of this section of the cycle is an inorganic phosphate is removed from 1,3BPG as a hydrogen ion and two electrons are added to the compound+.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] In complete reverse of the glycolytic pathway reaction, the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase catalyses the reduction of the carboxyl group of 1,3BPG to form an aldehyde instead.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] This reaction also releases an inorganic phosphate molecule which is subsequently used as energy for the donation of electrons from the conversion of NADPH to NADP+.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Overseeing this latter stage of the reaction is the enzyme glyceraldehyde-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] During normal metabolism in human erythrocytes, ≈19% of the 1,3BPG produced does not go any further in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] It is instead shunted through the Luebering–Rapoport pathway involving the reduction of ATP in the red blood cells.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] During this alternate pathway it is made into a similar molecule called 2,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid (2,3BPG).
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] 2,3BPG is used as a mechanism to oversee the efficient release of oxygen from hemoglobin.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Levels of this 1,3BPG will raise in a patient's blood when oxygen levels are low as this is one of the mechanisms of acclimatization.
[src:aldolase-b/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Low oxygen levels trigger a rise in 1,3BPG levels which in turn raises the level of 2,3BPG which alters the efficiency of oxygen dissociation from hemoglobin.
[src:aldolase-b/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] It requires thiamine diphosphate (ThDP) as cofactor.
[src:aldolase-b/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] The entry is intended to mainly represent the class of enzymes examplified by human HACL1 (gene), which can catalyze both reactions and is found in the peroxisome.
[src:aldolase-b/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] It is required for handling phytanic acid.
[src:aldolase-b/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] Humans and other mammals have another similar enzymes that only catalyzes reaction (2) and is instead located in the endoplasmic reticulum, HACL2 (gene).
[src:aldolase-b/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] This one participates in phytosphingosine degradation.
[src:aldolase-b/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] Both the baker's yeast and the fission yeast have a *Pxp1* gene corresponding to this activity, as annotated on UniProt by sequence similarity (not by experimental characterization of enzyme activity).
[src:aldolase-b/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] These two versions are known to appear in the cytoplasm and the peroxisome based on experimental evidence listed in UniProt.
[src:aldolase-b/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] Both the mouse-ear cress (Arath) and the rice have a *HACL* gene corresponding to this activity, as annotated on UniProt by sequence similarity (not by experimental characterization of enzyme activity).
[src:aldolase-b/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] The Arath version is experimentally detected in the cytoplasm, peroxisome, and plastid.
[src:aldolase-b/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] UniProt reports that the social ameoba *Dictyostelium discoideum* has a version of this enzyme, as annotated on UniProt by sequence similarity (not by experimental characterization of enzyme activity).
[src:aldolase-b/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] 2-phosphoglyceric acid is an intermediate that is part of the glycolysis pathway, and it is converted into phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) by an enolase.
[src:aldolase-b/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] There are three types of enolase enzymes that are able to catalyze the conversion of 2-phosphoglyceric acid into PEP, which are alpha-enolase, beta-enolase, and gamma-enolase.
[src:aldolase-b/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Studies have found that Alpha-enolase is the most common enolase, so it is often the specific enolase used to convert 2-phosphoglyceric acid into PEP.
[src:aldolase-b/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Alpha-enolase catalyzes this conversion process by acting as a Hydrolase, which means that alpha-enolase removes a water molecule from the 2-phosphoglyceric acid in order to form PEP.
[src:aldolase-b/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 5.4.2.1 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-b/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00631 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-b/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 4.2.1.11 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-b/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00074 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The HMGCL gene encodes a 34.5-kDa protein that is localized to the mitochondrion and peroxisome.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Multible isoforms of the proteins are known due to alternative splicing.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The major isoform (isoform 1) is most highly expressed in the liver whereas isoform 2 is found in energy-demanding tissues including the brain, heart, and skeletal muscle.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Structure of the HMGCL protein has been resolved by X-ray crystallography at 2.1-Å resolution, and reveals that the protein may function as a dimer.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Substrate access to the active site of the HMGCL enzyme involves substrate binding across a cavity located at the C-terminal end of a beta barrel structure.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] In addition, the lysine 48 residue which is mutated in patients with 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA lyase deficiency is also found to be necessary for substrate binding.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Electron density was observed indicating a bound metal ion, presumably Mg2+ due to its inclusion in the crystallization medium.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The enzyme activity is dependent on the presence of the metal this was determined by mutating His233 to Ala233 and Asp42 to Asn42 and experiencing catalytic deficiency of 6.4E−3 kcat/kM and 1.3E−5 kcat/kM respectively.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The substrate binding site includes arginine 41 making a salt bridge to the carboxylate of the hydroxyglutaric acid closest to metal ion.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] A mutation in Arg 41 results in a drastic decrease of catalytic activity.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The extreme decrease in efficiency suggests the direct involvement in the chemistry of the catalytic reaction.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] This Arg41 also salt bridges to Glu72 to fold into the correct position and charge balance Arg41 to bind to the substrate.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The HMGCL protein plays an essential role in breaking down dietary proteins and fats for energy.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] and requires a divalent metal ion as co-factor.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Deficiency HMG-CoA lyase deficiency causes hypoketotic hypoglycemia similar to that is caused by HMGCS2 mutations but also leads to organic acid accumulation and metabolic acidosis due to altered leucine metabolism.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] This disorder can be mistaken for Reye syndrome because of the symptoms of vomiting, lethargy, and convulsions.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Mutations in the *HMGCL* gene cause 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA lyase deficiency (HMGCLD), a rare autosomal recessive inborn error of metabolism characterized by disruption of ketogenesis and L-leucine catabolism.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] To-date more than 30 different mutations including missense mutations of different residues have been associated with patients with HMGCLD in diverse families and ethnicities.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] HMGCLD typically presents in the first year of the patient's life after a fasting period.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Clinical acute symptoms include vomiting, seizures, metabolic acidosis, hypoketotic hypoglycemia, and lethargy.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] HMGCL interacts with itself to form homodimers and homotetramers.
[src:aldolase-b/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] It is also shown in yeast two-hybrid experiments to interact with DNAJA1.
[src:aldolase-b/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the glycolytic pathway, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is dephosphorylated to form 3-phosphoglyceric acid in a coupled reaction producing two ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:aldolase-b/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] The single phosphate group left on the 3-PGA molecule then moves from an end carbon to a central carbon, producing 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:aldolase-b/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This phosphate group relocation is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate mutase, an enzyme that also catalyzes the reverse reaction.
[src:aldolase-b/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the light-independent reactions (also known as the Calvin-Benson cycle), two 3-phosphoglycerate molecules are synthesized.
[src:aldolase-b/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] RuBP, a 5-carbon sugar, undergoes carbon fixation, catalyzed by the rubisco enzyme, to become an unstable 6-carbon intermediate.
[src:aldolase-b/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This intermediate is then cleaved into two, separate 3-carbon molecules of 3-PGA.
[src:aldolase-b/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] G3P eventually reacts to form the sugars such as glucose or fructose or more complex starches.
[src:aldolase-b/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Glycerate 3-phosphate (formed from 3-phosphoglycerate) is also a precursor for serine, which, in turn, can create cysteine and glycine through the homocysteine cycle.
[src:aldolase-b/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] 3-phosphoglycerate can be separated and measured using paper chromatography as well as with column chromatography and other chromatographic separation methods.
[src:aldolase-b/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] It can be identified using both gas-chromatography and liquid-chromatography mass spectrometry and has been optimized for evaluation using tandem MS techniques.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] This enzyme has been of particular interest because it is a classic example of how pKa values of ionizable groups in the enzyme active site can be significantly perturbed.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Specifically, the pKa value of lysine 115 in the active site is unusually low, allowing for the formation of a Schiff base intermediate and catalysis.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Acetoacetate decarboxylase is an enzyme with major historical implications, specifically in World War I and in establishing the state of Israel.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] During the war the Allies needed pure acetone as a solvent for nitrocellulose, a highly flammable compound that is the main component in gunpowder.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] In 1916, biochemist and future first president of Israel Chaim Weizmann was the first to isolate *Clostridium acetobutylicum*, a Gram-positive, anaerobic bacteria in which acetoacetate decarboxylase is found.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Weizmann was able to harness the organism's ability to yield acetone from starch in order to mass-produce explosives during the war.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] This led the American and British governments to install the process devised by Chaim Weizmann in several large plants in England, France, Canada, and the United States.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Through Weizmann's scientific contributions in World War I, he became close with influential British leaders educating them of his Zionist beliefs.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] One of them was Arthur Balfour, the man after whom the Balfour Declaration—the first document pronouncing British support in the establishment of a Jewish homeland—was named.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] The production of acetone by acetoacetate decarboxylase-containing or clostridial bacteria was utilized in large-scale industrial syntheses in the first half of the twentieth century.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] In the 1960s, the industry replaced this process with less expensive, more efficient chemical syntheses of acetone from petroleum and petroleum derivatives.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] However, there has been a growing interest in acetone production that is more environmentally friendly, causing a resurgence in utilizing acetoacetate decarboxylase-containing bacteria.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Similarly, isopropanol and butanol fermentation using clostridial species is also becoming popular.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Acetoacetate decarboxylase is a 365 kDa complex with a homododecameric structure.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] The overall structure consists of antiparallel β-sheets and a central seven-stranded cone-shaped β-barrel.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] The core of this β-barrel surrounds the active site in each protomer of the enzyme.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] The active site, consisting of residues such as Phe27, Met97, and Tyr113, is mostly hydrophobic.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] However, the active site does contain two charged residues: Arg29 and Glu76.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Arg29 is thought to play a role in substrate binding, while Glu76 is thought to play a role in the orienting the active site for catalysis.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] The overall hydrophobic environment of the active site plays a critical role in favoring the neutral amine form of Lys115, a key residue involved in the formation of a Schiff base intermediate.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Another important lysine residue, Lys116, is thought to play an important role in the positioning of Lys115 in the active site.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Through hydrogen bonds with Ser16 and Met210, Lys116 positions Lys115 in the hydrophobic pocket of the active site to favor the neutral amine form.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Acetoacetate decarboxylase from *Clostridium acetobutylicum* catalyzes the decarboxylation of acetoacetate to yield acetone and carbon dioxide (Figure 1).
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] The reaction mechanism proceeds via the formation of a Schiff base intermediate, which is covalently attached to lysine 115 in the active site.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] The first line of support for this mechanism came from a radiolabeling experiment in which researchers labeled the carbonyl group of acetoacetate with 18O and observed that oxygen exchange to water, used as the solvent, is a necessary part of decarboxylation step.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] These results provided support that the mechanism proceeds through a Schiff base intermediate between the ketoacid and an amino acid residue on the enzyme.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Further research led to the isolation of an active site peptide sequence and identification of the active site lysine, Lys115, that is involved in the formation of the Schiff base intermediate.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Additionally, later experiments led to the finding that maximum activity of the enzyme occurs at pH 5.95, suggesting that the pKa of the ε-ammonium group of Lys115 is significantly perturbed in the active site.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] If the pKa were not perturbed downward, the lysine residue would remain protonated as an ammonium cation, making it unreactive for the nucleophilic addition necessary to form the Schiff base.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Building upon this finding, Westheimer et al. directly measured the pKa of Lys115 in the active site using 5-nitrosalicylaldehyde (5-NSA) .
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Reaction of 5-NSA with acetoacetate decarboxylase and subsequent reduction of the resulting Schiff base with sodium borohydride led to the incorporation of a 2-hydroxy-5-nitrobenzylamino reporter molecule in the active site (Figure 2).
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Titration of the enzyme with this attached reporter group revealed that the pKa of Lys115 is decreased to 5.9 in the active site.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] These results were the basis for the proposal that the perturbation in the pKa of Lys115 was due to its proximity to the positively charged ε-ammonium group of Lys116 in the active site.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] A nearby positive charge could cause unfavorable electrostatic repulsions that weaken the N-H bond of Lys115.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Westheimer et al.'s proposal was further supported by site-directed mutagenesis studies.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] When Lys116 was mutated to cysteine or asparagine, the pKa of Lys115 was found to be significantly elevated to over 9.2, indicating that positively charged Lys116 plays a critical role in determining the pKa of Lys115.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Although a crystal structure was not yet solved to provide structural evidence, this proposal was widely accepted and cited as a textbook example of how the active site can be precisely organized to perturb a pKa and affect reactivity.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] In 2009, a crystal structure of acetoacetate decarboxylase from *Clostridium acetobutylicum* was solved, allowing Westheimer et al.'s proposal to be evaluated from a new perspective .
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] From the crystal structure, researchers found that Lys 115 and Lys 116 are oriented in opposite directions and separated by 14.8 Å (Figure 3).
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] This distance makes it unlikely that the positive charge of Lys116 is able to affect the pKa of Lys115.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Instead through hydrogen bonds with Ser16 and Met210, Lys116 likely holds Lys115 into position in a hydrophobic pocket of the active site.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] This positioning disrupts the stability of the protonated ammonium cation of Lys115, suggesting that the perturbation of Lys115's pKa occurs through a 'desolvation effect'.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Acetoacetate decarboxylase is inhibited by a number of compounds.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Acetic anhydride performs an electrophilic attack on the critical catalytic residue, Lys115, of acetoacetate decarboxylase to inactivate the enzyme.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] The rate of inactivation was assessed through the hydrolysis of the synthetic substrate 2,4-dinitrophenyl propionate to dinitrophenol by acetoacetate decarboxylase.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] In the presence of acetic anhydride, the enzyme is inactivated, unable to catalyze the hydrolysis reaction 2,4-dinitrophenyl propionate to dinitrophenol.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Acetonylsulfonate acts as a competitive inhibitor (KI=8.0 mM ) as it mimics the characteristics of the natural substrate, acetoacetate (KM=8.0 mM).
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] The monoanion version of acetonylphosphonate is also a good inhibitor (KI=0.8mM), more efficient than the acetonylphosphonate monoester or dianion.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] These findings indicate that active site is very discriminatory and sterically restricted.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Hydrogen cyanide seems to be an uncompetitive inhibitor, combining with Schiff's base compounds formed at the active site.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Addition of carbonyl compounds to the enzyme, in the presence of hydrogen cyanide, increases hydrogen cyanide's ability to inhibit acetoacetate decarboxylase, suggesting that carbonyl compounds readily form Schiff's bases at the active site.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Hydrogen cyanide is most potent as an inhibitor at pH 6, the optimum pH for the enzyme, suggesting that the rate-limiting step of catalysis is the formation of the Schiff base intermediate.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Beta-diketones appear to inhibit acetoacetate decarboxylase well but slowly.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Acetoacetate decarboxylase has a KM for acetoacetate of 7×10−3 M whereas the enzyme has a KI for benzoylacetone of 1.9×10−6 M.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] An enamine is most likely formed upon interaction of beta-diketones with free enzyme.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] The reaction of acetoacetate decarboxylase with *p*-chloromercuriphenylsulfonate (CMS) results in decreased catalytic activity upon two equivalents of CMS per enzyme subunit.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] CMS interacts with two sulfhydryl groups located on each enzyme subunit.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Further inactivation occurs upon addition of a third equivalent of CMS per subunit.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Addition of free cysteine to the inhibited enzyme is able to reverse CMS inhibition of acetoacetate decarboxylase.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] While this enzyme has not been purified from human tissue, the activity was shown to be present in human blood serum.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] The acetoacetate decarboxylase activity is mainly attributed to human serum albumin, however, the activity is about $10^{-4}$ times that of real acetoacetate decarboxylase (*C. acetobutylicum*).
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] In humans and other mammals, the conversion of acetoacetate into acetone and carbon dioxide by acetoacetate decarboxylase is a final irreversible step in the ketone-body pathway that supplies the body with a secondary source of energy.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] In the liver, acetyl co-A formed from fats and lipids are transformed into three ketone bodies: acetoacetate, D-β-hydroxybutyrate and acetone.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Acetoacetate and D-β-hydroxybutyrate are exported to non-hepatic tissues, where they are converted back into acetyl-coA and used for fuel.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Acetone and carbon dioxide on the other hand are exhaled, and not allowed to accumulate under normal conditions.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Acetoacetate and D-β-hydroxybutyrate freely interconvert through the action of D-β-hydroxybutyrate dehydrogenase.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Subsequently, one function of acetoacetate decarboxylase may be to regulate the concentrations of the other, two 4-carbon ketone bodies.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Ketone body production increases significantly when the rate of glucose metabolism is insufficient in meeting the body's energy needs.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Such conditions include high-fat ketogenic diets, diabetic ketoacidosis, or severe starvation.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Under elevated levels of acetoacetate and D-β-hydroxybutyrate, acetoacetate decarboxylase produces significantly more acetone.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Acetone is toxic, and can accumulate in the body under these conditions.
[src:aldolase-b/acetoacetate-decarboxylase] Elevated levels of acetone in the human breath can be used to diagnose diabetes.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Coenzyme A (CoASH or CoA) consists of a β-mercaptoethylamine group linked to pantothenic acid (vitamin B5) through an amide linkage and 3'-phosphorylated ADP.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] The acetyl group (indicated in blue in the structural diagram on the right) of acetyl-CoA is linked to the sulfhydryl substituent of the β-mercaptoethylamine group.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] This thioester linkage is a "high energy" bond, which is particularly reactive.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Hydrolysis of the thioester bond is exergonic (−31.5 kJ/mol).
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] CoA is acetylated to acetyl-CoA by the breakdown of carbohydrates through glycolysis and by the breakdown of fatty acids through β-oxidation.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA then enters the citric acid cycle, where the acetyl group is oxidized to carbon dioxide and water, and the energy released is captured in the form of 11 ATP and one GTP per acetyl group.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Konrad Bloch and Feodor Lynen were awarded the 1964 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries linking acetyl-CoA and fatty acid metabolism.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Fritz Lipmann won the Nobel Prize in 1953 for his discovery of the cofactor coenzyme A.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is a metabolic intermediate that is involved in many metabolic pathways in an organism.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] It is produced during the breakdown of glucose, fatty acids, and amino acids, and is used in the synthesis of many other biomolecules, including cholesterol, fatty acids, and ketone bodies.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also a key molecule in the citric acid cycle, which is a series of chemical reactions that occur in the mitochondria of cells and is responsible for generating energy in the form of ATP.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] In addition, acetyl-CoA is a precursor for the biosynthesis of various acetyl-chemicals, acting as an intermediate to transfer an acetyl group during the biosynthesis of those acetyl-chemicals.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also involved in the regulation of various cellular mechanisms by providing acetyl groups to target amino acid residues for post-translational acetylation reactions of proteins.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] The acetylation of CoA is determined by the carbon sources.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, glycolysis takes place rapidly, thus increasing the amount of citrate produced from the citric acid cycle.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] This citrate is then exported to other organelles outside the mitochondria to be broken into acetyl-CoA and oxaloacetate by the enzyme ATP citrate lyase (ACL).
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] This principal reaction is coupled with the hydrolysis of ATP.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels CoA is acetylated using acetate by acetyl-CoA synthetase (ACS), also coupled with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Ethanol also serves as a carbon source for acetylation of CoA utilizing the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Degradation of branched-chain ketogenic amino acids such as valine, leucine, and isoleucine occurs.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] These amino acids are converted to α-ketoacids by transamination and eventually to isovaleryl-CoA through oxidative decarboxylation by an α-ketoacid dehydrogenase complex.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Isovaleryl-CoA undergoes dehydrogenation, carboxylation and hydration to form another CoA-derivative intermediate before it is cleaved into acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Additionally, malonyl-CoA decarboxylase (MCD), present in the cytosol, contributes to the extramitochondrial acetyl-CoA pool by converting malonyl-CoA into acetyl-CoA.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, acetyl-CoA is produced through glycolysis.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Pyruvate undergoes oxidative decarboxylation in which it loses its carboxyl group (as carbon dioxide) to form acetyl-CoA, giving off 33.5 kJ/mol of energy.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] The oxidative conversion of pyruvate into acetyl-CoA is referred to as the **pyruvate dehydrogenase reaction**.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] It is catalyzed by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Other conversions between pyruvate and acetyl-CoA are possible.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] For example, pyruvate formate lyase disproportionates pyruvate into acetyl-CoA and formic acid.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels, the production of acetyl-CoA is linked to β-oxidation of fatty acids.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Fatty acids are first converted to acyl-CoA.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Acyl-CoA is then degraded in a four-step cycle of oxidation, hydration, oxidation and thiolysis catalyzed by four respective enzymes, namely acyl-CoA dehydrogenase, enoyl-CoA hydratase, 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase, and thiolase.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] The cycle produces a new fatty acid chain with two fewer carbons and acetyl-CoA as a byproduct.
[src:aldolase-b/acetyl-coa] Within mitochondria, MCD similarly facilitates acetyl-CoA production by decarboxylating malonyl-CoA, thereby supporting metabolic flexibility during low-glucose states.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] In humans, aldolase B is encoded by the *ALDOB* gene located on chromosome 9.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] The gene is 14,500 base pairs long and contains 9 exons.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Defects in this gene have been identified as the cause of hereditary fructose intolerance (HFI).
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] The generic fructose bisphosphate aldolase enzyme cleaves a 6-carbon fructose sugar into two 3-carbon products in a reverse aldol reaction.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] This reaction is typified by the formation of a Schiff base intermediate with a lysine residue (lysine 229) in the active site of the enzyme; the formation of a Schiff base is the key differentiator between Class I (produced by animals) and Class II (produced by fungi and bacteria) aldolases.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] After Schiff base formation, the fourth hydroxyl group on the fructose backbone is then deprotonated by an aspartate residue (aspartate 33), which results in an aldol cleavage.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Schiff base hydrolysis yields two 3-carbon products.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Depending on the reactant, F1P or FBP, the products are DHAP and glyceraldehyde or glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate, respectively.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] The ΔG°’ of this reaction is +23.9 kJ/mol.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Though the reaction may seem too uphill to occur, it is of note that under physiological conditions, the ΔG of the reaction falls to close to or below zero.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] For example, the ΔG of this reaction under physiological conditions in erythrocytes is -0.23 kJ/mol.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Aldolase B is a homotetrameric enzyme, composed of four subunits with molecular weights of 36 kDa with local 222 symmetry.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Each subunit has a molecular weight of 36 kDa and contains an eight-stranded α/β barrel, which encloses lysine 229 (the Schiff-base forming amino acid that is key for catalysis).
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Though the majority of the overall structure of the aldolase enzyme is conserved amongst the three isozymes, four regions of the generic aldolase enzyme have been identified to be highly variable among isozymes.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Such regions have been denoted isozyme-specific regions (ISR1-4).
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] These regions are thought to give isozymes their specificities and structural differences.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] ISRs 1-3 are all found in exon 3 of the *ALDOB* gene.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] ISR 4 is the most variable of the four and is found at the c-terminal end of the protein.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] ISRs 1-3 are found predominantly in patches on the surface of the enzyme.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] These patches do not overlap with the active site, indicating that ISRs may change specific isozyme substrate specificity from a distance or cause the C-terminus interactions with the active site.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] A recent theory suggests that ISRs may allow for different conformational dynamics in the aldolase enzyme that account for its specificity.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Aldolase B plays a key role in carbohydrate metabolism as it catalyzes one of the major steps of the glycolytic-gluconeogenic pathway.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Though it does catalyze the breakdown of glucose, it plays a particularly important role in fructose metabolism, which occurs mostly in the liver, renal cortex, and small intestinal mucosa.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] When fructose is absorbed, it is phosphorylated by fructokinase to form fructose 1-phosphate.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Aldolase B then catalyzes F1P breakdown into glyceraldehyde and DHAP.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] After glyceraldehyde is phosphorylated by triose kinase to form G3P, both products can be used in the glycolytic-gluconeogenic pathway, that is, they can be modified to become either glucose or pyruvate.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Though the mechanism aldolase B regulation is unknown, increased *ALDOB* gene transcription in animal livers has been noticed with an increase in dietary carbohydrates and decrease in glucagon concentration.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Genetic mutations leading to defects in aldolase B result in a condition called hereditary fructose intolerance.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Due to the lack of functional aldolase B, organisms with HFI cannot properly process F1P, which leads to an accumulation of F1P in bodily tissues.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] In addition to being toxic to cellular tissues, high levels of F1P traps phosphate in an unusable form that does not return to the general phosphate pool, resulting in depletion of both phosphate and ATP stores.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] The lack of readily available phosphate causes the cessation of glycogenolysis in the liver, which results in hypoglycemia.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] This accumulation also inhibits gluconeogenesis, further reducing the amount of readily available glucose.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] The loss of ATP leads to a multitude of problems including inhibition of protein synthesis and hepatic and renal dysfunction.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Patient prognosis, however, is good in cases of hereditary fructose intolerance.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] By avoiding foods containing fructose, sucrose, and sorbitol, patients can live symptom-free lives.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] HFI is recessively inherited autosomal disorder.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Approximately 30 mutations that cause HFI have been identified, and these combined mutations result in a HFI frequency of 1 in every 20,000 births.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Mutant alleles are a result of a number different types of mutations including base pair substitutions and small deletions.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] The most common mutation is A149P, which is a guanine to cytosine transversion in exon 5, resulting in the replacement of alanine at position 149 with proline.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] This specific mutant allele is estimated to account for 53% of HFI alleles.
[src:aldolase-b/aldolase-b] Other mutations resulting in HFI are less frequent and often correlated with ancestral origins.
